rosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatten","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatton  . This surname is also common among African Americans.","North German: habitational name from the name of an area of marshland between Oldenburg and Bremen."]},{"name":"Hattan","meanings":["English and Scottish (Argyll): variant of   Hatton  ."]},{"name":"Aton","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"]},{"name":"Heath","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Hatton was born in 1132, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Hatton, was 37 and his mother, Eleanor Crispin, was 33. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Erma Mathilda de Ville. He died in 1161, in England, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1132–1161":"1132–1161","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1141–Male":"1141–Surnud","1142–Male":"1142–Surnud","1149–Male":"1149–Surnud","1136–Female":"1136–Surnud","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1156–Male":"1156–Surnud","1158–1206":"1158–1206","1095–Male":"1095–Surnud","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","1190":"1190","1132":"1132","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","Abt 1158":"umbes 1158","abt 1154":"umbes 1154","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1206":"1206","1149":"1149","1158":"1158","1136":"1136","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","about 1156":"umbes 1156","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Hatton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Amington, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1132–1161":"1132–1161","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1130–1190":"1130–1190","1141–Male":"1141–Kuollut","1142–Male":"1142–Kuollut","1149–Male":"1149–Kuollut","1136–Female":"1136–Kuollut","1154–Male":"1154–Kuollut","1156–Male":"1156–Kuollut","1158–1206":"1158–1206","1095–Male":"1095–Kuollut","1100–Female":"1100–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1132":"1132","1154":"1154","1120":"1120","1142":"1142","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","Abt 1158":"noin 1158","abt 1154":"noin 1154","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1206":"1206","1149":"1149","1158":"1158","1136":"1136","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","about 1156":"noin 1156","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Hatton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hatton, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Amington, Warwickshire, England":"War